bib_record.title: Gamma-ray production by inelastic proton scattering on 16-O and 12-C

The tandem accelerator of the Institute
of Nuclear Physics at Orsay.
Data for the gamma angular distributions were
obtained by integrating the surface of the different
peaks of interest in the energy calibrated spectra.
Approximate peak shapes for a guide to the integration
were obtained by a MONTE CARLO simulation of the
experiment.
-By authors. EN in data section is the energy in the
center of the target.
The induced gamma rays were detected by a
set of eight high efficiency HP-Ge detectors with BGO
shielding for Compton suppression from the EUROGAM
phase I setup.
Overall systematic error of detector efficiency
The tandem accelerator of the Institute
of Nuclear Physics at Orsay.
A pulsed proton beam of 0.5-2 nA intensity.
For each event the energy signal and the time
difference between the detector signal and the beam
pulse were recorded in list mode.  The timing signal
was used to discriminate against neutron induced
signals in the detectors and against gamma rays
originating from beam interactions with collimators and
in the Faraday cup.
Detector system.
EUROGAM Phase I set.
In a first series of measurements a tantalum oxide
target of 500 mug/cm2 evaporated on a carbon backing
was used for proton energies from 8.4 to 12.2 MeV.
Above this energy, gamma rays resulting from reactions
with the Ta nuclei become too intense.  The target
stability was verified by regular measurements at a
proton energy of 10 MeV.  No deterioration of the
target during proton irradiation was observed.  In a
second series three different self-supporting collodion
foils (chemical composition C12+H16+N4+O18) of
thickness 0.7-3.5 mg/cm2 were used for measurements
with proton energies ranging from 8.6 to 20 MeV.   With
these targets a typical loss of the oxygen content of
50% in 12 hours irradiation with 0.5 nA proton beams
was observed.  The carbon content in both target
materials allowed the authors to obtain also
gamma-angular distributions for the 4.44 MeV transition
in 12C from Ep=8.4 MeV up to an energy, where the 4.44
MeV gamma-ray production from 16O(p,p+alpha+gamma)12C
stays negligible compared to the production of this
gamma-ray from inelastic proton scattering on 12C.

The error bars on the cross section include the
error of the Legendre polynom fit and for the data
taken with the collodion targets an additional error
from the normalization procedure.   This normalization
with respect to the 6.13 MeV data of Dyer et al
results in somewhat larger error bars for data points
obtained with the collodion targets in the region of
the narrow resonances below 12 MeV compared to the data
points obtained with the tantalumoxide target.  At
higher energy the excitation function for the 6.13  MeV
gamma-ray production gets smooth and the error due to
the relative normalization to the Dyer et al data is
reduced compared to the usual error from the Legendre
polynom fit.
